@node "1_0" "Introduction"
@{fg fill}@{u}1. Introduction@{uu}@{fg text}
AmiSystemRestore aims to give AmigaOS4 a similar ability to Window's very useful System Restore.  What it does is create Restore Points, which act as snapshots of your SYS:  partition (where the OS is stored).  If anything changes on your SYS:  partition, then you can roll it back to the time of the snapshot.

Why would you want to undo changes to your SYS:  partition?  Well, if you install a new program @{fg shadow}(or update an existing one)@{fg text}, you have no idea if any new libraries @{fg shadow}(or other changes)@{fg text} will have problems that may break existing programs.  A badly written installer might even replace libraries (etc) with older versions!

AmiSystemRestore allows you to undo @{b}all@{ub} recent changes @{fg shadow}(whether or not they were done by the installer)@{fg text}, and return SYS:  to an earlier point in time. Knowledgable users can be more selective about which changes are undone, with the warning that they need to know what they are doing!

If you are installing something using the official Installer system or AmiUpdate, then AmiSystemRestore will automatically create Restore Points for you (and Ringhio messages should notify you of this).  @{i}But if you are manually installing something, or are installing something using an AmigaDOS-script based installer, then you should manually create Restore Points before & after installation.@{ui}

To avoid creating a copy of the entire SYS:  partition for each Restore Point, AmiSystemRestore only stores the changes which happen after a Restore Point is created.  This means that AmiSystemRestore must be left running all the time. You @{b}can@{ub} stop it at any time, but it will not know about any changes that happen while it is not running, so this is not advised.  It is intended to be light weight, and so in general you should not notice any impact on your system.


@endnode

@node "2_0" "Minimum requirements"
@{fg fill}@{u}2. Minimum requirements@{uu}@{fg text}
* AmigaOS4.x with MUI installed (which should always be the case).

* Your SYS:  partition must have at least 15MB free.

* Your SYS:  partition should ONLY contain AmigaOS4 & related system files. @{i}It should NOT contain any third-party programs, and certainly no important user data.@{ui} (While this will not stop it from working, it will greatly complicate it's usage, because you will have to check what files Restoring will change.)


@endnode

@node "3_0" "Recommendations"
@{fg fill}@{u}3. Recommendations@{uu}@{fg text}
* Over 50MB free is recommended for the SYS:  partition.

* AmigaOS4.1 with at least Update 3, so that the toolbar looks correct (especially the images).


@endnode

@node "4_0" "WARNINGS - Please Read Carefully!"
@{fg fill}@{u}4. WARNINGS - Please Read Carefully!@{uu}@{fg text}
1.  AmiSystemRestore is @{b}not@{ub} an alternative to a full backup of your main OS partition, as it will not prevent corruption of the filingsystem, nor prevent formatting of the partition.

2.  Since AmiSystemRestore will typically undo @{b}all@{ub} changes made to your main OS partition (also known as SYS:), it is a bad idea to store user data on SYS:. The simplest way to avoid this problem is to not install any programs on SYS:.

If you @{b}already@{ub} have any programs (which store user data, such as emails) on SYS:, then please move them to a different partition @{fg shadow}(drag'n'drop them, check they work at the new location, and then delete the original on SYS:)@{fg text}.


@endnode

