@{"5.1. Errr, what does that mean?" link "5_1"}
@endnode

@node "5_1" "Errr, what does that mean?"
@{fg fill}@{u}5.1. Errr, what does that mean?@{uu}@{fg text}
In Plain English (and only as an aid to understanding) the above is intended to roughly mean:  AmiSystemRestore cost you nothing, so don't expect me to take responsibility for any problems that it causes you.  If it erases your harddisk, or directs your car into a ditch, that's your problem.  Of course, I try to ensure that AmiSystemRestore works well, but I can't guarantee it, so all use is soley at your risk.  Backups are a wonderful invention, make use of them.


@endnode

@node "6_0" "Installation"
@{fg fill}@{u}6. Installation@{uu}@{fg text}
Use the provided installation program.  If you run into any problems, then please contact me (see the @{"12. Last words & contact details" link "12_0"} chapter).

The first time AmiSystemRestore is run (typically when the installation finishes), you will be required to confirm that you understand & accept the above Legal Disclaimer.

@{"6.1. Manual installation" link "6_1"}
@endnode

@node "6_1" "Manual installation"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.1. Manual installation@{uu}@{fg text}
Manual installation is NOT supported.  In fact the whole idea of AmiSystemRestore is that you use automated installers without needing to worry about what they are doing!

But to put your mind at rest, here is roughly what the installer will do with the files inside the "files" folder:
* Tell AmiSystemRestore to quit, if it is already running.
* Create an AmiSystemRestore folder in your specified location (if not present).
* Copy "AmiSystemRestore" (including icon) to that folder.
* Copy "FakeInstaller" (no icon) to that folder.
* Copy this ReadMe to that folder.
* Copy "C/CreateRestorePoint" to your C: assignment.
* Copy any missing images from the "tbimages" folder to your tbimages: assignment.  Or if AISS is not installed, then create a "tbimages" folder in AmiSystemRestore's folder & copies all the images there instead.
* Add AmiSystemRestore to your WBStartUp (if you wanted it to).  @{fg shadow}(This needs OS4.1 Update 1 to work)@{fg text}
* Restart AmiSystemRestore, if it was previously running, or you chose to add it to the WBStartUp.

I also supply the source code of the installer ("Install.e"), which you can examine...  or even compile yourself using PortablE.


@endnode

@node "7_0" "Usage"
@{fg fill}@{u}7. Usage@{uu}@{fg text}
@{"7.1. An overview" link "7_1"}
@{"7.2. The Restore button" link "7_2"}
@{"7.3. The Prefs button" link "7_3"}
@{"7.4. How to use Restore when you cannot boot your normal OS partition" link "7_4"}
@{"7.5. AmiUpdate" link "7_5"}
@endnode

@node "7_1" "An overview"
@{fg fill}@{u}7.1. An overview@{uu}@{fg text}
When AmiSystemRestore is started, it opens a window.  You can iconify it by clicking on the window's close gadget.  You can have it iconised on start-up by changing a Preferences setting.

The first time it is run, it will create a hidden @{fg shadow}(iconless)@{fg text} AmiSystemRestore folder on SYS:, and automatically create the first Restore Point.  (While curious people may look inside this folder, please do not make any changes there.)


The GUI window has a row of buttons at the top:

  Create  Rename  Delete  Restore  Prefs  Quit

Below that is a scrollable list of the Restore Points (most recent at the top). And below that is a "Restore mode" choice gadget.  The buttons do the following:


* Create - This creates a new Restore Point.  It will ask you to provide a description, which should be something meaningful to you, such as "Before installing OWB v3.30", or "After updating z.library".  It is recommended that you create a Restore Point both before AND after installing something.

* Rename - This allows you to rename the selected Restore Point.

* Delete - This allows you to remove the selected Restore Point.  But please beware that typically this saves you very little disk space @{b}unless@{ub} you delete all of the oldest restore points.  Note that you cannot delete the most recent Restore Point.  When you click on the Delete button, it will ask for confirmation.

* Restore - If you have selected a Restore Point, then this button will be available to click on.  Normally it will offer to undo all changes made to SYS: since that Restore Point was created, effectively restoring it back to that point in time.  But it's behaviour changes if you switch "Restore mode" from Full to Limited.  See @{"7.2. The Restore button" link "7_2"} section for further details.

* Prefs - This opens the Preferences window, from which certain options can be changed.  See @{"7.3. The Prefs button" link "7_3"} section for further details.

* Quit - This closes AmiSystemRestore, and stops it from monitoring SYS:  for any changes.  It is NOT recommend that you do this, because it will not know about (nor be able to undo) changes made while it is not running.

@endnode

@node "7_2" "The Restore button"
@{fg fill}@{u}7.2. The Restore button@{uu}@{fg text}
If you have selected a Restore Point, then this button will be available to click on.  Normally it will open a window offering to undo all changes made to SYS:  after that Restore Point was created...  effectively restoring you back to that point in time.

But if you had changed the "Restore mode" @{fg shadow}(from Full)@{fg text} to Limited, then it would only offer to undo the changes made between the chosen Restore Point & the one after it.  This is useful for @{i}advanced users@{ui} who wish to only undo the changes made by certain installations (see later).

NOTE:  Limited mode also allows the selection of multiple restore points, which is useful for both Restoring & Deleting.


After clicking on the Restore button, the main window will be replaced by the Restore window.  This contains a list of all files which will be changed or deleted.

@{i}Knowledgable users@{ui} can examine this list, and untick any files that they don't want changed or deleted.  Even @{i}normal users@{ui} may wish to prevent their data files @{fg shadow}(stored on SYS:  against my advice!)@{fg text} from being restored.  Note that folders are shown in blue, and (un)ticking a folder will (un)tick all files inside it.  That is the only purpose of showing folders - a ticked folder does @{b}not@{ub} mean the folder itself will be deleted @{fg shadow}(or created)@{fg text}!

After you click on the OK button, it will create a new Restore Point @{fg shadow}(so that you can easily undo the restore)@{fg text}, and then it will actually make the changes. As each file is modified, it will be unticked.  You can click on the Cancel button at any time to stop it making (further) changes.  Once the restore is finished, all files should be unticked - if any are still ticked, then they could not be restored for some reason.  You can then click on the OK button to close the Restore window & re-open the main window.


By the way, if you had chosen to perform a @{b}Limited Restore@{ub} of (say) "Before installing X", then only the file changes that happened immediately after it would been ticked.  @{i}Beware@{ui} that this is not as easy to use as it sounds, because any changes @{fg shadow}(after the next restore point)@{fg text} made to other files in those folders will appear unticked (and so will not be restored) unless you manually tick them.  For example, if running the installed program created additional files, then those will appear unticked.

@endnode

@node "7_3" "The Prefs button"
@{fg fill}@{u}7.3. The Prefs button@{uu}@{fg text}
Clicking on the Prefs button opens a Prefs window.  It contains a number of options:

* Ticking "Iconify on start-up" means AmiSystemRestore will start iconified, instead of opening a window.

* The slider "Disk space usable for restore points" allows you to choose the maximum space that should be used for all restore points @{fg shadow}(it will delete the oldest restore points)@{fg text}.  In the event even this is too large, such that free space on SYS:  drops below 10MB, then it will automatically delete additional restore points.


Options for advanced users:

* Ticking "Show size of restore points" means that every restore point will show it's size.  When AmiSystemRestore is first started, measuring the size of all restore points can be quite demanding on the CPU & harddisk @{fg shadow}(although it's impact is reduced as it temporarily lowers it's priority to -1)@{fg text}.

* Ticking "Installer avoids creating empty restore points" means that installations using the official Installer won't create empty restore points. This is useful for advanced users who often run the Installer in Test mode.

* "Restore blacklist" shows which folders will NOT be restored, unless you manually tick them when doing a Restore.  By default AmiUpdate's Rollback folder is blacklisted.  In the future you will be able to add/remove folders.

@endnode

@node "7_4" "How to use Restore when you cannot boot your normal OS partition"
@{fg fill}@{u}7.4. How to use Restore when you cannot boot your normal OS partition@{uu}@{fg text}
If you are no-longer able to boot your normal OS partition, and you want to use AmiSystemRestore to Restore it back to an earlier point, then you need to follow these steps:

1. Boot from your OS4 installation CD, or from a backup partition.

2. You are advised to use SYS:Utilities/PartitionWizard to Check your normal OS partition has no filingsystem errors.  @{fg shadow}(Unfortunately this currently crashes on the X1000.)@{fg text}

3. Open a Shell, and enter the following command, where "OS4" should be changed to be the name of your normal OS4 partition:

  Assign SYS: OS4:

4. Now run AmiSystemRestore.  If it asks you to accept the Legal Disclaimer, then please say @{b}No@{ub}, because you did not assign SYS:  correctly (repeat step 3 again).

5. Restore to an earlier point.  When it has finished, wait a few seconds for harddisk activity to finish, and then perform a @{b}hard reset@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "7_5" "AmiUpdate"
@{fg fill}@{u}7.5. AmiUpdate@{uu}@{fg text}
AmiUpdate already has it's own "RollBack" system, and when it works (*) it should be better than AmiSystemRestore.  So if your problem came from an AmiUpdate update, then I recommend that you try using it's RollBack feature before AmiSystemRestore.  @{fg shadow}(* = the main reason it might not work is if the update script was not correctly written by the developer of the update.)@{fg text}

This RollBack feature is a bit hidden, so here is how to find it:

1.  Start Sys:Prefs/Updates (or from AmiUpdate's menu choose Project/Open preferences...).

2.  Click on the "Install and RollBack" tab.

3.  Click on the "Run RollBack..." button.

4.  In the new window, click on the date of the update, and then click on the update itself.

5.  You can now click on the Info button to see what files will be restored, or on the Rollback button to actually undo the update.

NOTE:  Before & after performing a RollBack, you may wish to create a restore point in AmiSystemRestore.


@endnode

@node "8_0" "Limitations"
@{fg fill}@{u}8. Limitations@{uu}@{fg text}
AmiSystemRestore has a few small limitations:

* Hyperion's new Python-based "Installation Utility" is not properly supported; a restore point will only be automatically created before the start of an installation (i.e.  none when it finishes), and the restore point will not have a meaningful name.  Improving this is not possible without Hyperion making a few small changes to their utility; if enough people request this of Hyperion, then hopefully they will be willing to do it!

* Changes to a file's protection flags, comments & time/date are not (yet) monitored.

* Creation & deletion of folders is not monitored (nor likely to be).  So Restoring will not delete previously-created folders, nor recreate previously-deleted empty folders.


@endnode

@node "9_0" "Is my problem caused by AmiSystemRestore?"
@{fg fill}@{u}9. Is my problem caused by AmiSystemRestore?@{uu}@{fg text}
@{"9.1. Known problems" link "9_1"}
@{"9.2. If you get a GrimReaper" link "9_2"}
@{"9.3. If your whole system just freezes" link "9_3"}
@{"9.4. If you get an unexpected error message" link "9_4"}
@{"9.5. If a program is running very slowly" link "9_5"}
@endnode

@node "9_1" "Known problems"
@{fg fill}@{u}9.1. Known problems@{uu}@{fg text}
None!

@endnode

@node "9_2" "If you get a GrimReaper"
@{fg fill}@{u}9.2. If you get a GrimReaper@{uu}@{fg text}
If you get a GrimReaper, then click on the "More" button, then click on the "Stack Trace" tab, then click on the "Generate Stack Trace" button.  If it mentions "AmiSystemRestore" in the list, especially right at the top of the list, then AmiSystemRestore is a prime suspect.

In that case, please click on the "Write Crash Log" button, then copy the Crash Log from RAM:  to harddisk & wait for harddisk activity to finish, then reboot, then email me the Crash Log, along with a description of the situation it happened in.

@{b}When sending me details of your problem@{ub}, please also send me a copy of the "Sys:AmiSystemRestore/debug.log" file (if it exists).  And don't forget to mention what OS4 machine you are using, and what version of OS4.

@endnode

@node "9_3" "If your whole system just freezes"
@{fg fill}@{u}9.3. If your whole system just freezes@{uu}@{fg text}
If you do @{b}not@{ub} get a GrimReaper, but your whole system just freezes, then it is difficult to tell.  First you need to work-out how to make the freeze happen, then you need to disable AmiSystemRestore in the WBStartup, then reboot, and then try to cause the freeze.  If it does @{b}not@{ub} freeze then AmiSystemRestore is a prime suspect.

In that case, please email me the exact instructions needed to cause the freeze.

@{b}When sending me details of your problem@{ub}, please also send me a copy of the "Sys:AmiSystemRestore/debug.log" file (if it exists).  And don't forget to mention what OS4 machine you are using, and what version of OS4.

@endnode

@node "9_4" "If you get an unexpected error message"
@{fg fill}@{u}9.4. If you get an unexpected error message@{uu}@{fg text}
If you do @{b}not@{ub} get a GrimReaper, but you get an unexpected error messages while using your Amiga (particularly if they mention AmiSystemRestore), then please send me a copy of the @{b}full@{ub} error message, and a description of the situation it happened in.

@{b}When sending me details of your problem@{ub}, please also send me a copy of the "Sys:AmiSystemRestore/debug.log" file (if it exists).  And don't forget to mention what OS4 machine you are using, and what version of OS4.

@endnode

@node "9_5" "If a program is running very slowly"
@{fg fill}@{u}9.5. If a program is running very slowly@{uu}@{fg text}
If you find a program runs very slowly @{fg shadow}(perhaps when doing something specific)@{fg text}, then you need to disable AmiSystemRestore in the WBStartup, then reboot, and then test the program again.  If it does @{b}not@{ub} run slowly, then AmiSystemRestore is a prime suspect.

In that case, please email the exact instructions needed to observe the slow speed problem.

@{b}When sending me details of your problem@{ub}, please also send me a copy of the "Sys:AmiSystemRestore/debug.log" file (if it exists).  And don't forget to mention what OS4 machine you are using, and what version of OS4.


@endnode

@node "10_0" "Developers"
@{fg fill}@{u}10. Developers@{uu}@{fg text}
If you are writing an installer that does not use the official Installer system (nor AmiUpdate), but another way (such as an AmigaDOS script), then no restore points will be automatically created.  The good news is that you can make this happen using the provided CreateRestorePoint command.  Here is how you would use it in an AmigaDOS script:


  ;# EARLY PART OF SCRIPT (before any changes are made to SYS:)
  
  ;create a restore point before any changes are made
  Which CreateRestorePoint *><>NIL:
  IF NOT WARN
  	CreateRestorePoint "Before DESCRIPTION"
  ENDIF
  
  ;# MIDDLE OF SCRIPT (where changes can be made to SYS:)
  
  ;create a restore point after all changes are made
  Which CreateRestorePoint *><>NIL:
  IF NOT WARN
  	CreateRestorePoint "After DESCRIPTION"
  ENDIF
  
  ;# FINAL PART OF SCRIPT (any house-keeping, such as might be done whether installation finishes or is cancelled)


This code will simply do nothing if AmiSystemRestore is not installed or not running, so it is quite safe.

"DESCRIPTION" should be replaced by a @{b}short@{ub} description of what is being installed.

The hash comments (;#) show where you would put the relevant parts of your code.

@{"10.1. Notes" link "10_1"}
@endnode

@node "10_1" "Notes"
@{fg fill}@{u}10.1. Notes@{uu}@{fg text}
The CreateRestorePoint command is normally installed in the C: folder.

If AmiSystemRestore is installed but not running, then CreateRestorePoint will not create a restore point.  And it will return with the WARN status @{fg shadow}(although I can't currently think of a good use for that!)@{fg text}.

Because of the above, @{b}in principle@{ub} your installer could use it's own copy of the CreateRestorePoint command (rather than rely on it being installed).  But this is @{b}not@{ub} recommended, because an old version of the command might not work with a new version of AmiSystemRestore (although I have done my best to ensure it will).


@endnode

@node "11_0" "The future"
@{fg fill}@{u}11. The future@{uu}@{fg text}
While AmiSystemRestore has a nice icon thanks to cha05e90, I would still be open alternative icons.

AmiSystemRestore is now very close to my original vision, so I don't have much planned.  Here are a few ideas I am @{b}considering@{ub}:

* Auto-create a restore point if none has been created within the last X days (user configurable).

* For emergency recovery, if AmiSystemRestore has not been used before on SYS: then offer the option to temporarily use a different SYS partition (that already has AmiSystemRestore), rather than the user having to manually assign SYS:. Must not confuse first-time users.

* A better GUI (and perhaps use ReAction).

* Add some tricky speed optimisations, but only once I am sure AmiSystemRestore is very stable.

* I may try porting it to AROS or MorphOS when (if?) PortablE is able to generate plain C code (instead of C++ code).  @{fg shadow}(It is not possible to patch those OSes from C++ code, due to register parameter limitations of GCC.)@{fg text}


If you are interested in any of these ideas, or have any suggestions of your own, then feel free to email me!  Your input may help me decided what to do next.


@endnode

@node "12_0" "Last words & contact details"
@{fg fill}@{u}12. Last words & contact details@{uu}@{fg text}
If you have any problems with AmiSystemRestore, then please let me know!  You can contact me by email, using the address given on this web page:

@{"cshandley.co.uk/email" system "OpenURL URL \"http://cshandley.co.uk/email\""}

If for some reason you cannot email me, then I can be found on AmigaWorld.net & www.Amigans.net as "ChrisH".  I suggest you PM me on AmigaWorld.net, as I may not notice forum posts (nor PMs on Amigans.net!).


@{"12.1. Thanks to" link "12_1"}
@endnode

